        <h2>Stage 1: Collection and Evaluation</h2>
        <p>Old laptops are collected through drop-off programs, recycling events, or manufacturer take-back services. Each device is assessed to determine whether it can be reused, refurbished, or needs to be dismantled for material recovery.</p>

        <h2>Stage 2: Secure Data Destruction</h2>
        <p>Before any hardware is reused or recycled, data security comes first. Certified recyclers ensure all hard drives are wiped using industry-standard software or physically destroyed to prevent data breaches.</p>

        <h2>Stage 3: Disassembly and Sorting</h2>
        <p>Technicians or automated systems carefully dismantle the laptop. Components such as batteries, circuit boards, memory chips, and displays are separated. Hazardous materials like lithium or lead-based components are isolated for safe handling.</p>

        <h2>Stage 4: Material Recovery and Reuse</h2>
        <p>Extracted components are either reused in other electronics or broken down further. Metals like aluminum, copper, and rare earth elements are smelted and purified. Plastics may be shredded and repurposed into new devices or consumer goods.</p>

        <h2>Conclusion: Extending Value, Reducing Harm</h2>
        <p>Recycling laptops responsibly not only conserves precious resources but also helps prevent toxic waste from harming our ecosystems. When handled correctly, even outdated devices can have a second life. So next time your laptop slows down, think of recycling as a powerful, eco-conscious choice.</p>
